docs.lead_paragraph: Mr. NICHOLSON, of Tennessee, held the attention of the Senate yesterday, speaking upon Mr. BROWN'S resolution. There was little of novelty in his remarks. He regarded Mr. SEWARD as the source of Brownism and Helperism; pronounced the Republican movement an attempt of Northern capital to divert Northern labor from the vindication of its own rights : and saw no escape from the mischievous tendencies of the Republican Party.

docs.lead_paragraph: The last earthly honors were yesterday paid to the remains of the great man who has just gone from among us. Escorted by the noblest and highest in the land, the body of MACAULAY was left to mingle its dust with those of the great of past days who slumber in peace beneath Westminster Abbey.

byline.original: Special Dispatch to the New-York Times. WASHINGTON, Sunday, Jan. 29

docs.snippet: The entire body of Republicans who had voted for Mr.SHEEMAN, with only one or two exceptions, met in caucus at the Capitol yesterday.  Hon. CHARLES F. ADAMS presided, and Mr. COLFAX efficiated as Secretary.
